{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JbF7De3yrtELzMnNwsb5bL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So Elasticsearch has HTTPS only (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: \"true\"). But the auth-checker readiness probe uses `http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_security/_authenticate` (HTTP not HTTPS). This means the auth-checker's readiness probe is also failing due to TLS mismatch.\n\nWait, but my task says \"ensure auth-checker becomes healthy after the rotation\". So the auth-checker might not be healthy right now for two reasons:\n1. Password mismatch (it uses `elastic-password` which has `elasticpass`, but maybe Elasticsearch is already using a different password?)\n2. Protocol mismatch (HTTP vs HTTPS)\n\nActually, both Elasticsearch and auth-checker are currently pulling from the same `elastic-password` secret containing `elasticpass`, so they should have matching credentials. But auth-checker is trying to connect via HTTP while Elasticsearch only accepts HTTPS. Let me check the auth-checker deployment to see if there's something I'm missing about how it's configured.\n\nThe readiness probe is attempting to authenticate against the Elasticsearch endpoint, but it's using an HTTP connection to a service that has TLS enabled. Since Elasticsearch has `xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: \"true\"`, it won't accept plain HTTP connections—they either get redirected or rejected entirely. So the protocol mismatch is the real blocker here, not necessarily the password itself. Let me check the service definition to see if es-http might be exposing an HTTP endpoint alongside HTTPS.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2231,"cache_read_input_tokens":32606,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2231},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"